"reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]</a></sup>According to these texts, time is cyclic, which repeats itself forever.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]</a></sup></p>\n<p></p>\n<div id="toc" class="toc">\n<div class="toctitle">\n<h2>Contents</h2>\n</div>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-1"><a href="#Time_units"><span class="tocnumber">1</span> <span class="toctext">Time units</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-2"><a href="#Sidereal_metrics"><span class="tocnumber">1.1</span> <span class="toctext">Sidereal metrics</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-3 tocsection-3"><a href="#Small_units_of_time_used_in_the_Vedas"><span class="tocnumber">1.1.1</span> <span class="toctext">Small units of time used in the Vedas</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-4"><a href="#Lunar_metrics"><span class="tocnumber">2</span> <span class="toctext">Lunar metrics</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-5"><a href="#Tropical_metrics"><span class="tocnumber">3</span> <span class="toctext">Tropical metrics</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-6"><a href="#Reckoning_of_time_among_other_entities"><span class="tocnumber">4</span> <span class="toctext">Reckoning of time among other entities</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-7"><a href="#Among_the_Pit.E1.B9.9Bs_.28forefathers.29"><span class="tocnumber">4.1</span> <span class="toctext">Among the Pit\xe1\xb9\x9bs (<i>forefathers</i>)</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-8"><a href="#Among_the_Devas"><span class="tocnumber">4.2</span> <span class="toctext">Among the Devas</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-9"><a href="#For_Brahma"><span class="tocnumber">4.3</span> <span class="toctext">For Brahma</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-10"><a href="#Four_Yugas"><span class="tocnumber">5</span> <span class="toctext">Four Yugas</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-11"><a href="#Current_Date"><span class="tocnumber">6</span> <span class="toctext">Current Date</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-12"><a href="#Calculating_the_elapsed_time_since_current_Brahma.27s_creation"><span class="tocnumber">6.1</span> <span class="toctext">Calculating the elapsed time since current Brahma\'s creation</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-13"><a href="#See_also"><span class="tocnumber">7</span> <span class="toctext">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-14"><a href="#References"><span class="tocnumber">8</span> <span class="toctext">References</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-15"><a href="#External_links"><span class="tocnumber">9</span> <span class="toctext">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<p></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Time_units">Time units</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Time units">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="thumb tright">\n<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="/wiki/File:HinduMeasurements.svg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/HinduMeasurements.svg/200px-HinduMeasurements.svg.png" width="200" height="857" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/HinduMeasurements.svg/300px-HinduMeasurements.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/HinduMeasurements.svg/400px-HinduMeasurements.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="248" data-file-height="1063" /></a>\n<div class="thumbcaption">\n<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:HinduMeasurements.svg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>\nHindu measurements in <a href="/wiki/Logarithm" title="Logarithm">logarithmic</a> scale.</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>Various units of time are used across the <a href="/wiki/Vedas" title="Vedas">Vedas</a>, Srimad Bagwat Purana,<a href="/wiki/Vishnu_Puran" class="mw-redirect" title="Vishnu Puran">Vishnu Puran</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mahabharata" title="Mahabharata">Mahabharata</a>, <a href="/wiki/Suryasidhanta" class="mw-redirect" title="Suryasidhanta">Suryasidhanta</a> etc.A summary of the Hindu metrics of time (<i><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">k\xc4\x81la</span> vyavah\xc4\x81ra</i>) follows.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]</a></sup></p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Sidereal_metrics">Sidereal metrics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Sidereal metrics">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<table class="wikitable">\n<tr>\n<th colspan="2">Unit</th>\n<th>Definition</th>\n<th>Relation to SI units</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Truti</th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xa4\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa5\x81\xe0\xa4\xa4\xe0\xa4\xbf</th>\n<td><a href="/wiki/Base_unit_(measurement)" title="Base unit (measurement)">Base unit</a></td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 0.031 \xc2\xb5s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Renu</th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa5\x87\xe0\xa4\xa3\xe0\xa5\x81</th>\n<td>60 Truti</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 1.86 \xc2\xb5s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Lava</th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xb2\xe0\xa4\xb5</th>\n<td>60 Renu</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 0.11 ms</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>L\xc4\xabk\xe1\xb9\xa3aka</th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xb2\xe0\xa5\x80\xe0\xa4\x95\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb7\xe0\xa4\x95</th>\n<td>60 Lava</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 6.696 ms</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Lipta</th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xb2\xe0\xa4\xbf\xe0\xa4\xaa\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xa4\xe0\xa4\xbe</th>\n<td rowspan="2">60 Leekshaka</td>\n<td rowspan="2">\xe2\x89\x88 0.401 s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Vipala</th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xb5\xe0\xa4\xbf\xe0\xa4\xaa\xe0\xa4\xb2</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Pala</span></th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xaa\xe0\xa4\xb2</th>\n<td rowspan="3">60 Lipta</td>\n<td rowspan="3">\xe2\x89\x88 24.1056 s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Vigha\xe1\xb9\xadi</span></th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xb5\xe0\xa4\xbf\xe0\xa4\x98\xe0\xa4\x9f\xe0\xa4\xbf</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Vin\xc4\x81d\xc4\xab</span></th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xb5\xe0\xa4\xbf\xe0\xa4\xa8\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xa1\xe0\xa5\x80</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Gha\xe1\xb9\xadi</span></th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\x98\xe0\xa4\x9f\xe0\xa4\xbf</th>\n<td rowspan="3">60 Vigha\xe1\xb9\xadi</td>\n<td rowspan="3">\xe2\x89\x88 24 min</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">N\xc4\x81d\xc4\xab</span></th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xa8\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xa1\xe0\xa5\x80</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Danda</span></th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xa6\xe0\xa4\xa3\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xa1</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Muh\xc5\xabrta</span></th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xae\xe0\xa5\x81\xe0\xa4\xb9\xe0\xa5\x82\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xa4</th>\n<td>2 Gha\xe1\xb9\xadi</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 48 min</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th rowspan="2">Nak\xe1\xb9\xa3atra Ahor\xc4\x81tram (Sidereal Day)</th>\n<th rowspan="2">\xe0\xa4\xa8\xe0\xa4\x95\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb7\xe0\xa4\xa4\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb0 \xe0\xa4\x85\xe0\xa4\xb9\xe0\xa5\x8b\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xa4\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa4\xae\xe0\xa5\x8d</th>\n<th>60 Gha\xe1\xb9\xad\xc4\xab</th>\n<th>\xe2\x89\x88 24 h</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>30 Muh\xc5\xabrta</th>\n<th>\xe2\x89\x88 24 h</th>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<table class="wikitable">\n<caption>Alternate system</caption>\n<tr>\n<th>Unit</th>\n<th>Definition</th>\n<th>Relation to SI units</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Truti</th>\n<td>Base unit</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 35.5 \xc2\xb5s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Tatpara</th>\n<td>100 Truti</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 3.55 ms</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Nimesha</th>\n<td>30 Tatpara</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 106.7 ms</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>K\xc4\x81\xe1\xb9\xa3\xe1\xb9\xadh\xc4\x81</th>\n<td>30 Nimesha</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 3.2 s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Kal\xc4\x81</th>\n<td>30 K\xc4\x81\xe1\xb9\xa3\xe1\xb9\xadh\xc4\x81</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 1.6 min</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Muh\xc5\xabrta</th>\n<td>30 Kal\xc4\x81</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 48 min</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Nak\xe1\xb9\xa3atra Ahor\xc4\x81tram (Sidereal Day)</th>\n<td>30 Muh\xc5\xabrta</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 24 h</td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Small_units_of_time_used_in_the_Vedas">Small units of time used in the Vedas</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Small units of time used in the Vedas">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>\n<table class="wikitable">\n<tr>\n<th>Unit</th>\n<th>Definition</th>\n<th>Relation to SI units</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>Param\xc4\x81\xe1\xb9\x87u</i></td>\n<td>Base unit</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 26.3 \xc2\xb5s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>A\xe1\xb9\x87u</i></td>\n<td>2 Param\xc4\x81\xe1\xb9\x87u</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 52.67 \xc2\xb5s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>Trasare\xe1\xb9\x87u</i></td>\n<td>3 A\xe1\xb9\x87u</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 158 \xc2\xb5s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>Tru\xe1\xb9\xadi</i></td>\n<td>3 Trasare\xe1\xb9\x87u</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 474 \xc2\xb5s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>Vedha</i></td>\n<td>100 Tru\xe1\xb9\xadi</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 47.4 ms</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>Lava</i></td>\n<td>3 Vedha</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 0.14 s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>Nime\xe1\xb9\xa3a</i></td>\n<td>3 Lava</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 0.43 s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>K\xe1\xb9\xa3a\xe1\xb9\x87a</i></td>\n<td>3 Nimesha</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 1.28 s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>K\xc4\x81\xe1\xb9\xa3\xe1\xb9\xadh\xc4\x81</i></td>\n<td>5 K\xe1\xb9\xa3a\xe1\xb9\x87a</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 6.4 s</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>Laghu</i></td>\n<td>15 K\xc4\x81\xe1\xb9\xa3\xe1\xb9\xadh\xc4\x81</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 1.6 min</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>Danda</i></td>\n<td>15 Laghu</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 24 min</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>Muh\xc5\xabrta</i></td>\n<td>2 Danda</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 48 min</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>Ahor\xc4\x81tram</i> (Day)</td>\n<td>30 Muh\xc5\xabrta</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 24 h</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Masa (Month)</th>\n<th>30 Ahor\xc4\x81tram</th>\n<th>\xe2\x89\x88 30 days</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Ritu (Season)</th>\n<th>2 Masa</th>\n<th>\xe2\x89\x88 2 months</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Ayana</th>\n<th>3 Ritu</th>\n<th>\xe2\x89\x88 6 months</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Samvatsara (Year)</th>\n<td rowspan="2">2 Ayana</td>\n<td rowspan="2">\xe2\x89\x88 365 days<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]</a></sup></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>Ahor\xc4\x81tram of Deva</th>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Lunar_metrics">Lunar metrics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Lunar metrics">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul>\n<li>A <i><a href="/wiki/Tithi" title="Tithi">Tithi</a></i> or <a href="/wiki/Lunar_day" title="Lunar day">lunar day</a> is defined as the time it takes for the <a href="/wiki/Longitude" title="Longitude">longitudinal</a> <a href="/wiki/Angle" title="Angle">angle</a> between the <a href="/wiki/Moon" title="Moon">moon</a> and the Sun to increase by 12<a href="/wiki/Degree_(angle)" title="Degree (angle)">\xc2\xb0</a>.Tithis begin at varying times of day and vary in duration from approximately 19 to approximately 26 hours.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]</a></sup></li>\n<li>A <i>Paksa</i> (also <i><a href="/wiki/Paksha" title="Paksha"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Pak\xe1\xb9\xa3a</span></a></i>) or <a href="/wiki/Lunar_fortnight" class="mw-redirect" title="Lunar fortnight">lunar fortnight</a> consists of 15 tithes.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]</a></sup></li>\n<li>A <i><a href="/wiki/Masa" title="Masa"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">M\xc4\x81sa</span></a></i> or <a href="/wiki/Lunar_month" title="Lunar month">lunar month</a> (approximately 29.5 days) is divided into 2 <i><a href="/wiki/Paksha" title="Paksha"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Pak\xe1\xb9\xa3a</span></a></i>s: the one between <a href="/wiki/New_moon" title="New moon">new moon</a> and <a href="/wiki/Full_moon" title="Full moon">full moon</a> (waxing) is called <i>gaura</i> or (bright) or <i><a href="/wiki/Shukla_paksha" class="mw-redirect" title="Shukla paksha"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">\xc5\x9aukla Pak\xe1\xb9\xa3a</span></a></i>; the one between full moon and new moon (waning) <i>K\xe1\xb9\x9bi\xe1\xb9\xa3h\xe1\xb9\x87a</i> (dark) <i>paksha</i><sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]</a></sup></li>\n<li>A <i><a href="/wiki/Ritu_(Hindu_calendar)" class="mw-redirect" title="Ritu (Hindu calendar)"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">\xe1\xb9\x9aitu</span></a></i> (or <i>season</i>) is 2 <i><a href="/wiki/Masa" title="Masa"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">M\xc4\x81sa</span></a></i><sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">[8]</a></sup></li>\n<li>An <i>Ayana</i> is 3 <a href="/wiki/Ritu_(Hindu_calendar)" class="mw-redirect" title="Ritu (Hindu calendar)"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">\xe1\xb9\x9aitu</span>s</a><sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]</a></sup></li>\n<li>A year is two <i>Ayanas</i><sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]</a></sup></li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Tropical_metrics">Tropical metrics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Tropical metrics">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul>\n<li>A <i>Y\xc4\x81ma</i> = 1/4 of a day (light) or night [ = 7\xc2\xbd Gratis (\xe0\xa4\x98\xe0\xa4\x9f\xe0\xa4\xbf) = 3\xc2\xbe <i>Muhurta</i>s = 3 <b><a href="/wiki/Hour" title="Hour"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Hora</span></a></b>s (\xe0\xa4\xb9\xe0\xa5\x8b\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa4\xbe) <i>]</i></li>\n<li>Eight <i>Y\xc4\x81mas</i> make half of the day (either day or night)</li>\n<li>An <i>Ahor\xc4\x81tra</i> is a tropical day (Note: A day is considered to begin and end at sunrise, not midnight.)<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]</a></sup></li>\n</ul>\n<table class="wikitable">\n<tr>\n<th colspan="2">Name</th>\n<th>Definition</th>\n<th>Equivalence</th>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><i>Yama</i></td>\n<td>\xe0\xa4\xaf\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xae</td>\n<td>\xc2\xbcth of a day (light) or night</td>\n<td>\xe2\x89\x88 3 hours</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<th>S\xc4\x81vana Ahor\xc4\x81tram</th>\n<th>\xe0\xa4\xb8\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xb5\xe0\xa4\xa8 \xe0\xa4\x85\xe0\xa4\xb9\xe0\xa5\x8b\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa4\xbe\xe0\xa4\xa4\xe0\xa5\x8d\xe0\xa4\xb0\xe0\xa4\xae\xe0\xa5\x8d</th>\n<th>8 Yamas</th>\n<th>1 Solar day</th>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Reckoning_of_time_among_other_entities">Reckoning of time among other entities</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Reckoning of time among other entities">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Among_the_Pit.E1.B9.9Bs_.28forefathers.29">Among the Pit\xe1\xb9\x9bs (<i>forefathers</i>)</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Among the Pit\xe1\xb9\x9bs (forefathers)">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>1 day of pitras = 1 solar <i>masa</i> (month)</li>\n<li>30 days of pitras = 1 month of pitras</li>\n<li>12 months of pitras = 1 year of pitras</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The Lifespan of the pitras is 100 years of pitras (3,000 Solar years).<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]</a></sup></p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Among_the_Devas">Among the Devas</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Among the Devas">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>The life span of any Hindu <a href="/wiki/Deva_(Hinduism)" title="Deva (Hinduism)">deva</a> spans nearly (or more than) 4.5&#160;million years. Statistically, we can also look it as:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>12000 Deva Years = Life Span of Devas = 1 Mah\xc4\x81-Yuga.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]</a></sup></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The <a href="/wiki/Vishnu_Purana" title="Vishnu Purana"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Vi\xe1\xb9\xa3\xe1\xb9\x87u Pur\xc4\x81\xe1\xb9\x87a</span></a> Time measurement section of the <a href="/wiki/Vishnu_Purana" title="Vishnu Purana"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Vi\xe1\xb9\xa3\xe1\xb9\x87u Pur\xc4\x81\xe1\xb9\x87a</span></a> Book I Chapter III explains the above as follows:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>2 Ayanas (6-month periods, see above) = 1 human year or 1 day of the devas</li>\n<li>4,000 + 400 + 400 = 4,800 divine years (= 1,728,000 human years) = 1 <a href="/wiki/Satya_Yuga" title="Satya Yuga">Satya Yuga</a><sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]</a></sup></li>\n<li>3,000 + 300 + 300 = 3,600 divine years (= 1,296,000 human years) = 1 <a href="/wiki/Treta_Yuga" title="Treta Yuga">Treta Yuga</a><sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]</a></sup></li>\n<li>2,000 + 200 + 200 = 2,400 divine years (= 864,000 human years) = 1 <a href="/wiki/Dvapara_Yuga" title="Dvapara Yuga">Dvapara Yuga</a><sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">[16]</a></sup></li>\n<li>1,000 + 100 + 100 = 1,200 divine years (= 432,000 human years) = 1 <a href="/wiki/Kali_Yuga" title="Kali Yuga">Kali Yuga</a><sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]</a></sup></li>\n<li>12,000 divine year = 4 Yugas (= 4,320,000 human years) = 1 Mah\xc4\x81-Yuga (also is equaled to 12000 Daiva (divine) Yuga)<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]</a></sup></li>\n<li>[2*12,000 = 24,000 divine year = 12000 revolutions of sun around its dual]<sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">[19]</a></sup></li>\n</ul>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="For_Brahma">For Brahma</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: For Brahma">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>1000 Mah\xc4\x81-Yugas = 1 Kalpa = 1 day (day only) of Brahma</li>\n</ul>\n<p>(2 <i>Kalpas</i> constitute a day and night of Brahma, 8.64&#160;billion human years)</p>\n<ul>\n<li>30 days of Brahma = 1 month of Brahma (259.2&#160;billion human years)</li>\n<li>12 months of Brahma = 1 year of Brahma (3.1104&#160;trillion human years)</li>\n<li>50 years of Brahma = 1 Par\xc4\x81rdha (156,764,160,000,000 human years)</li>\n<li>2 parardhas = 100 years of Brahma = 1 Para = 1 Mah\xc4\x81-Kalpa (the lifespan of Brahma) (313,528,320,000,000 human years)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>One day of Brahma is divided into 1000 parts called <i>chara\xe1\xb9\x87as</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">[20]</a></sup></p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Four_Yugas">Four Yugas</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Four Yugas">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Yugas can be understood easily by the Set theory. Satya Yuga is the largest set &amp; other yugas are its subsets. It also implies that Satya/Truth exists in all Yugas. The <i>chara\xe1\xb9\x87as</i> are divided as follows:</p>\n<table class="wikitable mw-collapsible">\n<caption>The Four Yugas</caption>\n<tr>\n<td>4 chara\xe1\xb9\x87as (1,728,000 <a href="/wiki/Solar_year" class="mw-redirect" title="Solar year">solar years</a>)</td>\n<td><a href="/wiki/Satya_Yuga" title="Satya Yuga">Satya Yuga</a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3 chara\xe1\xb9\x87as (1,296,000 solar years)</td>\n<td><a href="/wiki/Treta_Yuga" title="Treta Yuga">Treta Yuga</a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2 chara\xe1\xb9\x87as (864,000 solar years)</td>\n<td><a href="/wiki/Dvapara_Yuga" title="Dvapara Yuga">Dvapara Yuga</a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1 chara\xe1\xb9\x87as (432,000 solar years)</td>\n<td><a href="/wiki/Kali_Yuga" title="Kali Yuga">Kali Yuga</a></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td colspan="2" style="font-size: 88%">Source: <a rel="nofollow" class="external autonumber" href="http://vedabase.net/sb/3/11/19/en1">[1]</a></td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n<div class="timeline-wrapper"><map name="timeline_6cfb812e707db1accbd1399251b7a012" id="timeline_6cfb812e707db1accbd1399251b7a012">\n<area shape="rect" href="/wiki/Kalki" coords="582,175,654,199" title="Kalki" alt="Kalki" />\n<area shape="rect" href="/wiki/Krishna" coords="457,157,542,181" title="Krishna" alt="Krishna" />\n<area shape="rect" href="/wiki/Balarama" coords="457,139,549,163" title="Balarama" alt="Balarama" />\n<area shape="rect" href="/wiki/Rama" coords="395,120,459,144" title="Rama" alt="Rama" />\n<area shape="rect" href="/wiki/Parashurama" coords="332,102,444,126" title="Parashurama" alt="Parashurama" />\n<area shape="rect" href="/wiki/Vamana" coords="270,84,348,108" title="Vamana" alt="Vamana" />\n<area shape="rect" href="/wiki/Narasimha" coords="207,65,305,89" title="Narasimha" alt="Narasimha" />\n<area shape="rect" href="/wiki/Varaha" coords="145,47,223,71" title="Varaha" alt="Varaha" />\n<area shape="rect" href="/wiki/Kurma" coords="82,29,154,53" title="Kurma" alt="Kurma" />\n<area shape="rect" href="/wiki/Matsya" coords="20,10,98,34" title="Matsya" alt="Matsya" /></map><img usemap="#timeline_6cfb812e707db1accbd1399251b7a012" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/timeline/6cfb812e707db1accbd1399251b7a012.png" /></div>\n<p>The cycle repeats itself, so altogether there are 1,000 cycles of Mah\xc4\x81-Yuga in one day of Brahma.</p>\n<dl>\n<dd>\n<ul>\n<li>One cycle of the above four <i>Yuga</i>s is one <b>Mah\xc4\x81-Yuga</b> (4.32&#160;million <a href="/wiki/Solar_year" class="mw-redirect" title="Solar year">solar years</a>)</li>\n<li>as is confirmed by the G\xc4\xabt\xc4\x81 \xc5\x9aloka 8.17 (statement) "sahasra-yuga-paryantam ahar yad brahma\xe1\xb9\x87o vidu\xe1\xb8\xa5 r\xc4\x81tri\xe1\xb9\x81 yuga-sahasr\xc4\x81nt\xc4\x81\xe1\xb9\x81 te \'ho-r\xc4\x81tra-vido jan\xc4\x81\xe1\xb8\xa5", meaning, a day of brahma is of 1000 Mah\xc4\x81-Yuga. Thus a day of Brahma, Kalpa, is of duration: 4.32 billion solar years. Two <i>Kalpa</i>s constitute a day and night (Adhi Sandhi) of <a href="/wiki/Brahma_(god)" class="mw-redirect" title="Brahma (god)">Brahma</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">[21]</a></sup></li>\n<li>A <i>Manvantara</i> consists of 71 Mah\xc4\x81-Yuga (306,720,000 solar years). Each Manvantara is ruled by a Manu.<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">[22]</a></sup></li>\n<li>After each Manvantara follows one <i><a href="/wiki/Sandhi" title="Sandhi"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Sa\xe1\xb9\x83dhi</span></a> K\xc4\x81la</i> of the same duration as a <i>K\xe1\xb9\x9bta Yuga</i> (1,728,000 = 4 Chara\xe1\xb9\x87as). (It is said that during a <a href="/wiki/Sandhi" title="Sandhi"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Sa\xe1\xb9\x83dhi</span></a> K\xc4\x81la, the entire earth is submerged in water.)<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]</a></sup></li>\n<li>A <i><a href="/wiki/Kalpa_(aeon)" title="Kalpa (aeon)">Kalpa</a></i> consists of a period of 4.32 Billion solar years followed by 14 Manvataras and <a href="/wiki/Sandhi" title="Sandhi"><span title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none">Sa\xe1\xb9\x83dhi</span></a> Kalas.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]</a></sup></li>\n<li>A day of Brahma equals</li>\n</ul>\n<dl>\n<dd>(14 times 71 Mah\xc4\x81-Yuga) + (15 \xc3\x97 4 Chara\xe1\xb9\x87as)</dd>\n<dd>= 994 Mah\xc4\x81-Yuga + (15 * 4800)</dd>\n<dd>= 994 Mah\xc4\x81-Yuga + (72,000 years)[deva years] / 6 = 12,000[deva years] viz. one maha yuga.</dd>\n<dd>= 994 Mah\xc4\x81-Yuga + 6 Mah\xc4\x81-Yuga</dd>\n<dd>= 1,000 Mah\xc4\x81-Yuga.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[25]</a></sup></dd>\n</dl>\n</dd>\n</dl>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Current_Date">Current Date</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Current Date">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Currently, 50 years of Brahma have elapsed. The last Kalpa at the end of 50th year is called Padma Kalpa. We are currently in the first \'day\' of the 51st year.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[26]</a></sup> This Brahma\'s day, Kalpa, is named as Shveta-Varaha Kalpa. Within this Day, six Manvantaras have already elapsed<sup id="cite_ref-Burgess.2C_Chapter_1.2C_Verse_22_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Burgess.2C_Chapter_1.2C_Verse_22-27">[27]</a></sup> and this is the seventh Manvantara, named as \xe2\x80\x93 Vaivasvatha Manvantara (or Sraddhadeva Manvantara). Within the Vaivasvatha Manvantara, 27 Mahayugas<sup id="cite_ref-Burgess.2C_Chapter_1.2C_Verse_22_27-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Burgess.2C_Chapter_1.2C_Verse_22-27">[27]</a></sup> (4 Yugas together is a Mahayuga), and the Krita,<sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[28]</a></sup> Treta and Dwapara Yugas of the 28th Mahayuga have elapsed. This Kaliyuga is in the 28th Mahayuga. This Kaliyuga began in the year 3102 BCE in the proleptic Julian Calendar.<sup id="cite_ref-Burgess.2C_p17_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Burgess.2C_p17-29">[29]</a></sup> Since 50 years of Brahma have already elapsed, this is the second Parardha, also called as Dvithiya Parardha.</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Calculating_the_elapsed_time_since_current_Brahma.27s_creation">Calculating the elapsed time since current Brahma\'s creation</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Calculating the elapsed time since current Brahma\'s creation">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>432000 \xc3\x97 10 \xc3\x97 1000 \xc3\x97 2 = 8.64&#160;billion years (2 Kalpa (day and night))</p>\n<p>8.64 \xc3\x97 10<sup>9</sup> \xc3\x97 30 \xc3\x97 12 = 3.1104 Trillion Years (1 year of Brahma)<br />\n3.1104 \xc3\x97 10<sup>12</sup> \xc3\x97 50 = 155.52&#160;trillion years (50 years of Brahma)</p>\n<p>(6 \xc3\x97 71 \xc3\x97 4320000) + 7 \xc3\x97 1.728 \xc3\x97 10^6 = 1852416000 years elapsed in first six Manvataras, and Sandhi Kalas in the current <a href="/wiki/Kalpa_(aeon)" title="Kalpa (aeon)">Kalpa</a></p>\n<p>27 \xc3\x97 4320000 = 116640000 years elapsed in first 27 Mahayugas of the current Manvantara</p>\n<p>1.728 \xc3\x97 10^6 + 1.296 \xc3\x97 10^6 + 864000 = 3888000 years elapsed in current Mahayuga</p>\n<p>3102 + 2017 = 5119 years elapsed in current Kaliyuga.</p>\n<p>So the total time elapsed since current Brahma is</p>\n<p>155520000000000 + 1852416000 + 116640000 + 3888000 + 5119 = <i><b>155,521,972,949,119 years</b></i></p>\n<p>(one hundred fifty-five trillion, five hundred twenty-one billion, nine hundred seventy-two million, nine hundred forty-nine thousand, one hundred nineteen years) as of 2018 AD</p>\n<p>Total age of Brahma is 100 (Brahma Years) which is equal to <i><b>313,528,320,000,000 Human years</b></i></p>\n<p>The current Kali Yuga began at midnight 17 February / 18 February in 3102 BCE in the <a href="/wiki/Proleptic_Julian_calendar" title="Proleptic Julian calendar">proleptic Julian calendar</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">[30]</a></sup> As per the information above about Yuga periods, only 5,119 years are passed out of 432,000 years of current Kali Yuga, and hence another 426,881 years are left to complete this 28th Kali Yuga of Vaivaswatha Manvantara.</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Hindu_units_of_time&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="noprint metadata navbox" role="navigation" aria-label="Portals" style="font-weight:bold;padding:0.4em 2em">\n<ul style="margin:0.1em 0 0">\n<li style="display:inline"><span style="display:inline-block;white-space:nowrap"><span style="margin:0 0.5em"><a href="/wiki/File:MontreGousset001.jpg" class="image"><img alt="MontreGousset001.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/45/MontreGousset001.jpg/24px-MontreGousset001.jpg" width="24" height="21" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/45/MontreGousset001.jpg/36px-MontreGousset001.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/45/MontreGousset001.jpg/48px-MontreGousset001.jpg 2x" data-fil